
# To-Dos

##
##
### Realtime joining chat when streams start and stop
##
##

  - event-subscriber
    - pros
      - realtime
      - reactive
      - scalable. Easier to handle connecting and disconnecting to a large amount of streamers with this logic
    - cons
      - requires open port/general internet connectivity. Current setup is a home network. This option would require
        either opening a HOME NETWORK up to the general internet, or finding an external host. Hosting is possible with
        GCP free tier IIRC

  - polling
    - pros
      - relatively simple logic, easy to understand
      - does not require open internet connectivity, safe to do on home network
    - cons
      - running a small script once every 5 minutes uses an excessive amount of resources to track casual streamers
      - not scalable. In a hypothetical scenario where the bot is used by 1000 streamers, that would be 1000 separate https
        requests to make every 5 minutes. This could open up the possibility of becoming rate-limited by the polled API
        or blacklisted entirely

 Overall I think this should wait until the bot is already on an external host like GCP. I believe there is a GCP-free-tier
 that would serve this project nicely. This isn't a big enough need to justify setting up external hosting for this
 functionality alone.

 What are the possible issues that the bot may run into by being always-connected? Does that open up the bot to hacks?
 Does it violate twitch terms & conditions?

